Nicaragua
------------
Date: 1 Oct 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: El Nuevo Diario [translated by MJ] [edited]
<http://www.elnuevodiario.com.ni/archivo/2001/octubre/01-octubre-2001/nacional/nacional21.html>

Dengue Increase in Rivas Causes Health Ministry to Issue Medical Alert
-------------------------------------------------------
The state of Rivas continues under the epidemiological alert instituted by
the Ministry of Health (MINSA) because of an increase in the number of
cases of dengue fever, especially in the municipalities of Tola, Rivas, and
Belen. During 2000, 114 cases of dengue fever were reported. To date, the
numbers for 2001 have reached 675 suspected cases.
In response to this situation, MINSA designated the region's local integral
healthcare systems (SILAIS) as "Sentinel Sites" with the purpose of
achieving swifter diagnosis, better patient care, and increased
epidemiological surveillance. It is particularly important to consider that
the state of Rivas is more sensitive to the disease, given its proximity to
the border with Costa Rica, where the population is affected by serotype 3
dengue virus, while serotype 2 is prevalent in Nicaragua.
Dr. Carlos Urbina, of the epidemiology unit of SILAIS, stated that this
project would provide the means to train laboratory technicians and to
designate a physician, a pediatrician, and an epidemiologist to care
directly for patients who consult health centers with symptoms of dengue
fever. Urbina added that at the end of October [2001], a delegation from
SILAIS, headed by Dr. Julio Flores, would meet with its counterparts in
Costa Rica, with whom they collaborate through a project on both sides of
the border (Proyecto Interfronterizo), which aims to control problems such
as vector transmission.
Although no cases of infection by serotype 3 dengue virus have been
detected in Rivas, the fact is that it affects the population of Costa
Rica, producing more severe symptoms than those produced by serotype 2.
Nonetheless, there is real risk, given that a large percentage of the
population of this region, and particularly of the municipality of Tola,
work in Costa Rica. Transportation between the 2 countries is easy and
these workers return home as frequently as possible (every month, every 3
months, every 6 months, or once a year). In addition to announcing that the
health education program will continue, Urbina called on the entire
population to participate in disease prevention programs, which include the
cleaning of empty lots and the elimination of stagnant pools of water,
which promote the proliferation of disease.
