Date: 3 Oct 2001 09:08:59 -1000
From: David Duffy <dduffy@hawaii.edu>
Source: Honolulu Advertiser 3 Oct 2001 [edited]
<http://www.HonoluluAdvertiser.com>

[It appears we still have little idea of the full extent of the current
outbreak in Hawaii, but this article suggests local transmission on Kauai,
Oahu, and the Big Island (Hawaii) on the west or Kona Coast. Some of these
cases are several months old. - David Duffy]
Dengue fever may be spreading in Hawaii
--------------------------------------------
State health officials offered more troubling news about the dengue fever
outbreak yesterday, saying they now have suspected locally transmitted
cases on O'ahu, Kaua'i, and the Big Island.
If these cases are confirmed by the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention [CDC], it means the epidemic will have spread outside Maui to
most of the rest of the state. "We are very concerned," said Health
Department spokeswoman Janice Okubo.
Previous confirmed cases on O'ahu, Kaua'i, and the Big Island involved
patients who were infected with the mosquito-borne virus while in foreign
countries. The new suspected cases involve patients with no recent travel
history.
As of noon yesterday, 19 cases of dengue fever have been laboratory
confirmed, all from East Maui. The latest are 3 cases in Ha'iku, Okubo
said. None of the confirmed East Maui cases has recent travel history off
island, verifying the first documented local transmission of dengue fever
in more than 50 years.
The number of suspected cases in the current outbreak has reached 116, a
figure that includes one case from Ka'a'awa, O'ahu; one from Anahola,
Kaua'i; and 4 from Kailua-Kona, Hawai'i. In all of the cases, the patients
had no recent travel history off their islands.
Officials have a rapid field test that has good success in predicting
whether the CDC will confirm a case of dengue. Only the Anahola case was
tested, and the results were positive, Okubo said. Okubo said the
department is conducting "high surveillance" on clinics and hospitals on
all islands and is planning to disseminate additional information to
educate the public across the state. That probably will include passing out
information at airports, she said.
Preventing further spread of dengue in Hawaii will require a sustained
community-based effort of mosquito control combined with judicious use of
insecticides, officials said. All Hawaii residents, not only East Maui
residents, are being urged to keep their properties free of sites where
mosquitoes can breed.
[Byline: Timothy Hurley]
