Dengue - Venezuela 20010808.1873
Date: 3 Oct 2001
From: Jaime Torres, ProMED-ESP
Source: El Universal [translated by MJ [edited
<http://noticias.eluniversal.com/2001/10/03/03404BB.shtml>

Number of Cases in Caracas Decreases
-----------------------------------------------
The number of cases of dengue fever in the metropolitan area has decreased.
However, the efforts against _A. aegypti_ must continue and now, more than
ever, it is necessary to destroy any breeding grounds.
This was the statement issued by Baldomero Vasquez, Health Secretary for
the Mayor's Office. The data obtained by the Mayor's Office show that
during epidemiological week 39 (between 21-27 Sep 2001), the number of
cases reported in Caracas decreased to a daily average of 164 cases,
compared to the previous epidemiological week (14-20 Sep 2001), during
which 190 cases were reported daily. Vasquez explained that during week 38,
there were 1458 infected persons, while there were 1151 cases during week
39, indicating a 21% reduction.
One of the goals is to apply preventive measures in every school.
Approximately 85% of the education centers in the metropolitan area have
been sprayed with insecticides. Of 1222 centers, 987 have been treated, and
it is hoped that by the end of this week, every school will have been
treated. The goal of the next phase is to maintain and extend protective
measures, which will be achieved through the participation of the school
community as the first front of attack against the vector.
